r shows that Shakespeare presents a convincing portrait of Rome in different eras of its history, contrasting the austere republic of Coriolanus, with its narrow horizons and martial virtues, and the cosmopolitan empire of Antony and Cleopatra, with its “immortal longings” and sophistication bordering on decadence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish dramaxRoman influences. 0aHistorical drama, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aenglish literature, comparative lit, literary studies, william shakespeare, playwright, writer, politics, roman plays, rome, political thinker, classical republican, philosophy, coriolanus, tragedy, caius marcius, antony and cleopatra, julius caesar, historical drama, history, general, military, volscians, hostility, banishment, mark, suicide, sicilian revolt, empire, emperor, republic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226469003423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226469003/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles